comment.body: Using `fetch_add` with starting key 0 will cause the first inserted value to get key 0, but subsequent calls will skip key 1 and start from key 1. Consider using `fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed)` and then subtracting 1, or initialize the counter to start from the desired first key minus 1.

The return type of `clone_instance` has changed from `Result<Vec<i32>>` to `Result<i32>`, but the code is attempting to access index `[0]` which no longer exists. The `[0]` indexing should be removed since the method now returns the reference directly.

issue.title: Create Modbus Devices for each listed connection point in Modbus configuration
issue.body:
### The problem

I've recently switched my Keba integration from the internal integration (based on unreliable UDP protocol) to Modbus TCP. So far this is far more stable and controllable, as TCP is stateful protocol. One thing that bothers me (and others: https://community.home-assistant.io/t/modbus-sensors-unique-id-and-device-support/373428) is, that we create a "device" in yaml, under which we place binary_sensors, sensors, switches, ...
If you then look in Settings - Devices, it only lists the sensors as entities, but does not list the "main" device. It would be cumbersome to have some correction of this. 
My config looks like this:

```
  - name: KEBAP30
    delay: 5
    timeout: 5
    type: tcp
    host: 192.168.1.102 # your callbox IP address goes here
    port: 502
    sensors:
      # Lesbare Sensoren
      - name: KebaP30_charging_state
        address: 1000
        scan_interval: 30
        data_type: uint32
        unique_id: KebaP30_charging_state
      - name: KebaP30_cable_state
        address: 1004
        scan_interval: 30
        data_type: uint32
        unique_id: KebaP30_cable_state

``` 

I would expect to see
- Device = KebaP30
   - Sensor: sensor.KebaP30_charging_state
   - Sensor: sensor.KebaP30_cable_state
  
I cannot fix this myself, but hope that you'll help the community and me. 
Many thanks. 

### What version of Home Assistant Core has the issue?

core-2024.10.1

### What was the last working version of Home Assistant Core?

_No response_

### What type of installation are you running?

Home Assistant OS

### Integration causing the issue

Modbus

### Link to integration documentation on our website

https://www.home-assistant.io/integrations/modbus

### Diagnostics information

_No response_

### Example YAML snippet

```yaml
- name: KEBAP30
    delay: 5
    timeout: 5
    type: tcp
    host: 192.168.1.102 # your callbox IP address goes here
    port: 502
    sensors:
      # Lesbare Sensoren
      - name: KebaP30_charging_state
        address: 1000
        scan_interval: 30
        data_type: uint32
        unique_id: KebaP30_charging_state
      - name: KebaP30_cable_state
        address: 1004
        scan_interval: 30
        data_type: uint32
        unique_id: KebaP30_cable_state
```


### Anything in the logs that might be useful for us?

issue.title: vk: Resource binding model rewrites [part 2 of 2]
issue.body:
Relates to https://github.com/RPCS3/rpcs3/issues/17277

### Changes
- Remove all per-draw UBO objects and replace with SSBO array-of-structs model. This removes a lot of descriptor bind operations completely.
- Avoid using more than a few bytes of data in push constants. Instead, we write a per-draw config and push a pointer offset to the next one. Restricting push constants memory to 4 bytes per draw has decent gains.
- Replace std::vector with rsx::simple_array for trivial storage. The latter has small-vector optimizations that drastically reduce the number of memory allocations done on the fly and gives a decent perf bump to both Vulkan and OpenGL.
- Other minor optimizations related to resource bindings.

Overall, a 10-20% boost is observed depending on the game. MESA drivers benefit the most here since they doesn't keep a state cache like the properietary ones so state changes are more expensive on those drivers.

issue.title: [Form] Difficult to discover how to validate a form, and have mandatory fields
issue.body:
### Current approach of how a developer can add validation to a form - 
1. For all mandatory fields mark all the respective components within the form as "Mark this field mandatory".
2. Disable the submit button using fx {{components.form1.isValid == false}}

### Pain Points
1. This is a tedious process because the user needs to click on every mandatory field and mark the respective component "Mandatory".
2. Figuring out how to validate the form also takes time. (Discovery is hard, feedback from seasoned developers is on similar lines)

### Possible tweaks ([PRD](https://app.clickup.com/37484951/v/dc/13qycq-2704/13qycq-1564?block=block-7d27b4ec-ed1f-45f7-964f-eb516babdc2c))
1. Add Validate form property in form (checkbox) - In the property panel we can have a validations property where we show all the fields (components) that are present within the form and give the user an option to mark them as mandatory from a single place.
2. Clicking on the checkbox adds the fx {{components.form1.isValid == false}} to the disable property of the chosen submit button automatically. 
3. One stop place for all mandatory fields: A better way is provide a one stop place where the user can select which fields are to made mandatory and which ones are to be kept optional.

### Sanity Checks
Please implement the following if not present - 
Need to have the following happen by default - 
1. Show Red asterisk against mandatory fields (need improved UX)
2. Show fields in red if user moves to another field without filling out mandatory field
